rComments: well-intentioned, emphasis on understanding general concepts. however, very unclear in homework expectations and marking, calls students out of the blue, and refusal to adapt. More focused on students presenting homework assignment in front of class (that can be wrong) then guiding us through the answer himself. the class became toxic.

Unfortunately, this was the most stressful class I've taken in my time in school. The professor's marking was extremely unclear on weekly assignments and most class time was spent wasting time (led to going over time almost every week). I've always struggled with economics, but this class was difficult for reasons other than the material.

Very unclear expectations - the professor does not provide clear grading criteria. His grading criteria is completely arbitrary. He is not malicious but he does not listen when you address these issues. This class is a headache.

This professor cannot provide any information as to how he actually grades. Can be very condescending. Demands that cameras on always on in class and calls out students and puts them on the spot. Classes go overtime and there is no substance to his lectures until the last 30 min. Spends too much time talking about the weather, unimportant things.
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Lots of homework', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: The professor grades completely arbitrarily, and takes off points for "literary style" and "innovation" for a description of a graph. In addition, his comments are unclear, he calls on students randomly and then always belittles their answer. His style is to let you learn from the textbook. I took him because of his reviews, but avoid him.

Seems friendly but kinda talks down to you. Grades homework with no rubric or point system. Feedback is illegible and unhelpful making it hard to do well or improve. Lectures are confusing, spent mostly reviewing homework by correcting ppl in front of the class, covers little new material each week. Refused to clarify questions on the midterm.

Professor Finnie was well-intentioned I think. However, his questions and feedback were very unclear, making it challenging to know how to succeed in this class. Additionally, he forces students to have their cameras on always and then will randomly call on them. This approach lacks respect and understanding towards students and is kind of mean.
The most caring professor I had in both undergraduate and graduate studies. He communicates the material very clearly and gives very valuable feedback.

His lectures can be confusing, His marking of assignments is not always clear. However, he was always willing to answer any questions outside of class that I might of have had. As well, participation matters, so be prepared to be called out of the blue to provide an answer to any question on the course material.
